<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><entry xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="entry_fætæg" xml:lang="os"><form type="lemma"><orth>fætæg</orth></form><sense><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru"><q>вождь</q></cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en"><q>leader</q></cit></sense><cit type="exampleGroup" corresp="#sense_fætæg." n=""><cit type="example"><quote>ūcy ræstæǵy Iræn sæ fætæg wyd Alǧ˳yz</quote><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru"><q>в то время вождем осетин был Алгуз</q></cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en"><q>at that time the leader of the Ossetians was Alguz</q></cit></cit><cit type="example" xml:lang="os-x-digor"><usg type="dialect"><lang/></usg><quote>woʒænæj ældar wæ zingæ fætæg</quote><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru"><q>алдар будет вашим знаменитым вождем</q></cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en"><q>the aldar will be your famous leader</q></cit><bibl><ref target="#src_Bes."/><biblScope>111</biblScope></bibl></cit><cit type="example" xml:lang="os-x-digor"><usg type="dialect"><lang/></usg><quote>qazar læg næ zewi næ zajuj fætæg</quote><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru"><q>ценный человек в нашей общей работе не остается вождем</q></cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en"><q>a valuable person in our common work does not remain a leader</q></cit><bibl><ref target="#src_Qazb."/><biblScope>35</biblScope></bibl></cit></cit><cit type="exampleGroup" corresp="#sense_." n=""><cit type="example"><quote>ūcy ræstæǵy Iræn sæ fætæg wyd Alǧ˳yz</quote><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru"><q>в то время вождем осетин был Алгуз</q></cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en"><q>at that time the leader of the Ossetians was Alguz</q></cit></cit><cit type="example" xml:lang="os-x-digor"><usg type="dialect"><lang/></usg><quote>woʒænæj ældar wæ zingæ fætæg</quote><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru"><q>алдар будет вашим знаменитым вождем</q></cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en"><q>the aldar will be your famous leader</q></cit><bibl><ref target="#src_Bes."/><biblScope>111</biblScope></bibl></cit><cit type="example" xml:lang="os-x-digor"><usg type="dialect"><lang/></usg><quote>qazar læg næ zewi næ zajuj fætæg</quote><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru"><q>ценный человек в нашей общей работе не остается вождем</q></cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en"><q>a valuable person in our common work does not remain a leader</q></cit><bibl><ref target="#src_Qazb."/><biblScope>35</biblScope></bibl></cit></cit><etym xml:lang="ru">Восходит к <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/><w>*paϑaka-</w></mentioned>, от <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/><w>раϑ-</w><gloss><q>путь</q></gloss></mentioned>; собственно „путеводитель“. Ср. <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/><w>paϑ-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/><w>path-, patha-</w><gloss><q>дорога</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w/><gloss><q>тропа</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w>pathaka-</w><gloss><q>путевед</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w/><gloss><q>путеводитель</q></gloss></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/><w>πάτος</w><gloss><q>дорога</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="grc"><w/><gloss><q>тропа</q></gloss></mentioned>,  и пр. В скифских диалектах были представлены, по-видимому, все три варианта основы ‘путь’: 1. %ipanti-%i (<mentioned xml:lang="xsc"><lang/><w>Παντικαπης</w></mentioned>; <bibl corresp="#ref_ОЯФ_I"><biblScope>175</biblScope></bibl>), 2. %ipantā-%i (ос. <xr><ref target="#entry_fændag"/></xr>), 3. %iраϑ-%i (<mentioned xml:lang="xsc"><lang/><w>Παταικος, Φιατακος</w></mentioned>, ос. <xr><ref target="#entry_fætæg"/></xr>; <bibl corresp="#ref_ОЯФ_I"><biblScope>176</biblScope></bibl>). %bСкиф.%b <mentioned xml:lang="xsc"><lang/><w>*раϑ-</w></mentioned> — вероятный источник германского слова для ‘тропы’: <mentioned xml:lang="de"><lang/><w>Pfad</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="en"><lang/><w>path</w></mentioned> и пр. (<bibl corresp=""><biblScope>%sKluge%s</biblScope></bibl>). Несостоятельно сближение с <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/><w>pati-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/><w>paiti-</w><gloss><q>господин</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl corresp="#ref_ZDMG"><biblScope>XLIII 672</biblScope></bibl>). Ср. <xr><ref target="#entry_fændag"/></xr>.%n<bibl corresp="#ref_ОЯФ_I"><biblScope>176</biblScope></bibl>.</etym><etym xml:lang="en">Traces back to <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/><w>*paϑaka-</w></mentioned>, from <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/><w>раϑ-</w><gloss><q>path</q></gloss></mentioned>; ‘guide’ proper. Cf. <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/><w>paϑ-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/><w>path-, patha-</w><gloss><q>road</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w/><gloss><q>trail</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w>pathaka-</w><gloss><q>guide</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w/><gloss><q>guidebook</q></gloss></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/><w>πάτος</w><gloss><q>road</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="grc"><w/><gloss><q>trail</q></gloss></mentioned>,  etc. In the Scythian dialects, apparently all three variants of the 'path' stem were represented: 1. %ipanti-%i (<mentioned xml:lang="xsc"><lang/><w>Παντικαπης</w></mentioned>; <bibl corresp="#ref_ОЯФ_I"><biblScope>175</biblScope></bibl>), 2. %ipantā-%i (Ossetic <xr><ref target="#entry_fændag"/></xr>), 3. %iраϑ-%i (<mentioned xml:lang="xsc"><lang/><w>Παταικος, Φιατακος</w></mentioned>, Ossetic <xr><ref target="#entry_fætæg"/></xr>; <bibl corresp="#ref_ОЯФ_I"><biblScope>176</biblScope></bibl>). <mentioned xml:lang="xsc"><lang/><w>*раϑ-</w></mentioned> is a likely source of the Germanic word for ‘trail’: <mentioned xml:lang="de"><lang/><w>Pfad</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="en"><lang/><w>path</w></mentioned> etc. (<bibl corresp=""/>). The relation with <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/><w>pati-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/><w>paiti-</w><gloss><q>master</q></gloss></mentioned> is untenable (<bibl corresp="#ref_ZDMG"><biblScope>XLIII 672</biblScope></bibl>). Cf. <xr><ref target="#entry_fændag"/></xr>.%n<bibl corresp="#ref_ОЯФ_I"><biblScope>176</biblScope></bibl>.</etym></entry>